'''Willard's sooty boubou''' ('''''Laniarius willardi''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Malaconotidae]], native to the [[Albertine Rift montane forests]].

== Description ==
The species was first described in 2010, based on five specimens, all collected by the [[Field Museum of Natural History]] and originally identified as the [[Mountain sooty boubou]] (''L. poensis''). Four were collected in 1997 on a private banana plantation in southern [[Uganda]], and the fifth was collected in [[Burundi]] in 1991. {{Sfn|Voelker et al|2010|p=679}}

The species' main distinct trait is its gray-to-blue-gray eye color, in comparison to the reddish-black to black eye color typically found in the Mountain sooty boubou.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|date=March 19, 2010|title=African bird discovery proves there is something new under the sun|work=ScienceDaily|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/03/100316101610.htm|access-date=June 18, 2021}}</ref>{{Sfn|Voelker et al|2010|p=679}} However, specimens collected as far back as 1910 were identified as having gray irises, but categorized as ''L. poensis''.<ref name=":0" /> The species was also identified as being genetically diagnosable, differing 11.5% in uncorrected sequence divergence from the co-located [[Albertine sooty boubou]].{{Sfn|Voelker et al|2010|p=678}} The species is named in honor of Field Museum of Natural History collections manager David Willard, with its common name also reflecting its uniform black plumage.{{Sfn|Voelker et al|2010|p=682}}

The species is also considered to be potentially threatened, due to occurring in a narrow elevational band between 1,200 and 2,000 meters that is heavily deforested for [[tea plantation]]s.<ref name=":0" />{{Sfn|Voelker et al|2010|p=685}}

